          "body": "Two of the chapter's most evocative images appear in its central and closing social-wisdom sections. Verse 14: 'The teaching of the wise is a fountain of life, to turn aside from the snares of death.' Torah (*torah*) of the wise — not merely information conveyed by a clever person, but the accumulated moral instruction of someone whose character has been shaped by wisdom — functions as a continuously flowing spring. The traveler who drinks from it is directed away from *moqesh mavet* (the snares of death) — the traps set along the road that appear safe but are lethal. The image is intensely practical: wisdom literature is not the adornment of an educated life but the navigation system without which the road ends badly. Verse 20 makes the same point through the sociology of companionship: 'He who walks with wise men will be wise, but the companion of fools will suffer harm.' The Hebrew *halakh* (to walk) denotes the sustained, habitual pattern of one's daily movement — not an occasional visit but a shared path. Wisdom and folly are both transmitted through association; they are caught as much as they are taught. The companion (*ro'eh*) of fools will be *raa* (broken, harmed) — the word suggests something being smashed or shattered. These two verses together constitute the chapter's social pedagogy: the source of wisdom is the teaching of the wise (v. 14), and the medium of wisdom's transmission is walking with them (v. 20)."
