          "body": "Verse 12 stands apart from the chapter's antithetical couplets in its emotional register and its explicit naming of the inner life. 'Hope deferred makes the heart sick, but desire fulfilled is a tree of life.' This is not primarily moral instruction but psychological observation — wisdom literature's recognition that the inner experience of waiting, longing, and receiving is morally significant. *Tochelet* (hope, what is waited for) drawn out (*mashakh*) over time makes the *lev* (heart, the seat of cognition and desire) *chalah* (sick, weak, exhausted). The image is of someone who has held out expectation for so long that the holding itself has become painful. The positive image is equally vivid: *taavah* (desire, craving) fulfilled (*ba'ah*, arrived, come) is a *ets chay* (tree of life) — the Eden image of the thing that sustains and renews life itself. The verse frames the chapter's entire account of satisfaction and want: the righteous person's appetite is satisfied (v. 25), the diligent soul is made fat (v. 4), the desire realized is sweet (v. 19) — all of these are elaborations of the tree-of-life image. The wicked path is the path of hope deferred indefinitely: craving without fulfillment (v. 4), a stomach in need (v. 25), a lamp going out before the satisfaction comes (v. 9). Proverbs 13 takes seriously that human beings are not motivated by abstract principle but by longing — and it argues that wisdom leads longing toward its actual satisfaction while folly perpetually defers it."
